{"key":"processedPost-10561040","value":{"id":10561040,"first":10558296,"last":10565145,"when":1245806947,"utime":"06/24/09 04:29 AM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><strong>hyphae said:</strong><br />If it's bright enough to read by that's all you need bright light is not necessary this species is phototropic light simply gives it direction and stimulates pinning nothing more.</blockquote><br />I strongly disagree. <br />After thousands of grows, I found that bright light stimulates a far better pinset and fatter, meatier caps with considerably more weight at harvest.&nbsp; Over the last year or so, many growers have switched from dim lights to bright fluorescent in the 6500 Kelvin range and have gone from mediocre harvests to stellar harvests.&nbsp; It really does make a big difference.&nbsp; In fact, five to ten minutes of direct sunlight per day also works wonders.<br />Wind currents and gravity actually tell the mushrooms which way to grow.&nbsp; Cubensis will fruit(poorly) in total darkness and the fruits nearly always form on the top surface, even in the absence of light.<br />RR","title":"Re: lighting"}}